class TreeNode {
    constructor(val, left=null, right=null) {
        this.val = val;
        this.left = left;
        this.right = right;
    }
}

function kthLargestLevelSum(root, k) {
    let levelSums = [];
    let q = [root];

    while (q.length > 0) {
        let levelSum = 0;
        let levelSize = q.length;
        for (let i = 0; i < levelSize; ++i) {
            let node = q.shift();
            levelSum += node.val;

            if (node.left) q.push(node.left);
            if (node.right) q.push(node.right);
        }

        levelSums.push(levelSum);
    }

    levelSums.sort((a, b) => b - a);
    return (k > levelSums.length ? -1 : levelSums[k-1]);
}
```

    We can use Breadth-First Search (BFS) to traverse the binary tree level by level. We calculate the sum of node values of each level and store them in an array. After the BFS traversal is complete, we sort the array in descending order and return the kth element or -1 if k is greater than the number of levels in the tree.

