    ```java
import java.util.*;

class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left;
    TreeNode right;
}

public int kthLargestLevelSum(TreeNode root, int k) {
    List<Integer> levelSums = new ArrayList<>();
    Queue<TreeNode> q = new LinkedList<>();
    q.add(root);

    while (!q.isEmpty()) {
        int levelSum = 0;
        int levelSize = q.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < levelSize; ++i) {
            TreeNode node = q.remove();
            levelSum += node.val;

            if (node.left != null) q.add(node.left);
            if (node.right != null) q.add(node.right);
        }

        levelSums.add(levelSum);
    }

    levelSums.sort(Collections.reverseOrder());
    return (k > levelSums.size() ? -1 : levelSums.get(k-1));
}
```

    We can use Breadth-First Search (BFS) to traverse the binary tree level by level. We calculate the sum of node values of each level and store them in an array. After the BFS traversal is complete, we sort the array in descending order and return the kth element or -1 if k is greater than the number of levels in the tree.
